Online Business Sales 2017-2019¶

Dataset is actual sales from online store between 2017-2019¶

Background: The datasets are from a unnamed business' online retail sales for the period 2017-2019. 1st dataset shows individual orders, 2nd dataset shows aggregated monthly data.¶

Tasks:¶

1. Loading data and cleaning data (if necessary)¶
2. Exploratory data analysis (EDA)¶
3. Data visualizations¶

In [17]:
# Grouping by product type and adding new columns

products_grouped = products.groupby("product_type").sum().reset_index()
products_grouped["gross_sales_per_unit"] = (
    products_grouped["gross_sales"] / products_grouped["net_qty"]
)
products_grouped["net_sales_per_unit"] = (
    products_grouped["total_net_sales"] / products_grouped["net_qty"]
)
products_grouped["pct_lost"] = (
    100
    - (
        products_grouped["net_sales_per_unit"]
        / products_grouped["gross_sales_per_unit"]
    )
    * 100
)
products_grouped["return_rate"] = (
    (products_grouped["returns"] / products_grouped["gross_sales"]) * 100
).abs()
products_grouped

In [22]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 5))
ax.scatter(
    products_grouped["net_qty"],
    products_grouped["total_net_sales"],
    color=colors[0],
    marker="s",
    label="Products",
)
ax.set_xlabel("Units Sold")
ax.set_ylabel("Total Net Sales")
plt.title("Units Sold vs Total Net Sales", size=16)
plt.grid(color="grey", linestyle="dotted")

for i in range(products_grouped.shape[0]):
    if products_grouped["net_qty"][i] > 250:
        plt.text(
            x=products_grouped["net_qty"][i] - 20,
            y=products_grouped["total_net_sales"][i],
            s=products_grouped["product_type"][i],
            ha="right",
            va="center",
        )
# Calculate the regression line
x = products_grouped["net_qty"]
y = products_grouped["total_net_sales"]
slope, intercept, r_value, p_value, std_err = linregress(x, y)
line = slope * x + intercept

# Plot the regression line
plt.plot(x, line, color=colors[9], linestyle="dotted", label="Regression line")
plt.legend()
plt.show()
  • Based on this scatter plot and regression line, we can see that such product types as Christmas, Kitchen, Jewelry, Art & Sculpture are under the regression line and it means that these product types are undervalued and could be sold for more.
  • On the other hand - product type "Basket" is earning more in sales than it should. It should be exploited in order to earn even more.

Cumulative Sum of Orders¶

In [31]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
plt.plot(
    monthly_data["year_month"],
    monthly_data["orders_run_total"],
    label="Orders",
    lw=2.5,
    color=colors[0],
)
plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontname="Bebas Neue")
plt.yticks(fontname="Bebas Neue")
plt.title("Cumulative Sum of Orders", fontname="Bebas Neue", size=16)
plt.grid(color="grey", linestyle="dotted")
# Calculate the regression line
x = np.array(range(len(monthly_data)))
y = monthly_data["orders_run_total"]
slope, intercept, r_value, p_value, std_err = linregress(x, y)
line = slope * x + intercept

# Plot the regression line
plt.plot(x, line, color=colors[9], linestyle="--", label="Regression line")
plt.legend()
plt.show()
In [32]:
# Getting the equation of the regression line and 'predicting' how many orders could be sold by the end of 2022

print(f"Regression line equation: y = {slope:.2f}x + {intercept:.2f}")
# Calculate the predicted y value for December 2022
x_dec_2022 = len(monthly_data) + 35  # assuming the last data point is December 2019
y_dec_2022 = slope * x_dec_2022 + intercept

# Print the predicted y value for December 2022
print(f"Predicted cumulative sum of orders for December 2022: {y_dec_2022:.0f}")

Regression line equation: y = 91.09x + -122.28
Predicted cumulative sum of orders for December 2022: 6345

By having a look at the cumulative sum of orders and creating a regression line to fit data the best, we could assume that if there are no significant changes in business, orders 3 years later (Dec 2022) would be around 6345.
